            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marcus Solana\u2019s sense of justice was forged in the steel mills and classrooms of Chicago\u2019s South Side. The only son of a union steelworker and a public school history teacher, he grew up with dinner-table debates about fairness, power, and the stories of those who went unheard. Watching local reporters expose neighborhood corruption on the nightly news, he saw a path. He pursued it with fierce determination, earning a Master's in Journalism from Northwestern University.\n\nHe cut his teeth on the gritty crime and politics beats in Chicago, but the seismic shifts of the late '90s dot-com boom lured him west. Marcus arrived in San Francisco a driven young reporter, fascinated and critical of the tech-fueled gold rush transforming the city. He joined a major newspaper, quickly earning a reputation for his relentless digging and refusal to be intimidated. His career was cemented by a series on city hall contract fraud that led to multiple indictments, making him a trusted and feared name in local journalism.\n\nNow 53 and the Lead Investigative Reporter for a prominent digital news outlet, Marcus\u2019s personal life bears the scars of his demanding career. A marriage ended amicably years ago, strained by late nights and the emotional weight of his stories. His greatest pride is his daughter, now a sophomore at UCLA, with whom he has a close, if long-distance, relationship.\n\nHis days are a disciplined routine. He leaves his Hayes Valley apartment, a rent-controlled unit he\u2019s held for over two decades, and takes the Muni 2.5 miles to his downtown office. He's witnessed his neighborhood morph from gritty to chic, a microcosm of the city he both loves and worries for. His work is his anchor, a way to hold power accountable in a city constantly reinventing itself. Marcus isn't dreaming of a different life; he\u2019s aspiring to land one more story big enough to shake the foundations of the powerful before mentoring the next generation to carry the torch."
